{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/6765.Virginia_Woolf", "name": "Virginia Woolf", "birth_date": "1882-01-25 00:00:00", "death_date": "1941-03-28 00:00:00", "genres": ["Essays", "Fiction"], "influences": ["Emil", "Mary Wollstonecraft", "Jane Austen", " William Shakespeare", "Anton Chekov", "James Joyce", "Walter Pater", "E.M. Forster", "Fyodor Dostoyevsky", "Emily Bront\u00eb", " Lev Tolstoy", "George Eliot", "Marcel Proust"], "avg_rating": 3.88, "num_reviews": 32745, "num_ratings": 577291, "about": "(Adeline) Virginia Woolf was an English novelist and essayist regarded as one of the foremost modernist literary figures of the twentieth century.During the interwar period, Woolf was a significant figure in London literary society and a member of the Bloomsbury Group. Her most famous works include the novels Mrs. Dalloway (1925), To the Lighthouse (1927), and Orlando (1928), and the book-length essay A Room of One's Own (1929) with its famous dictum, \"a woman must have money and a room of her own if she is to write fiction.\""}
