{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/6520834.Colleen_Oakes", "name": "Colleen Oakes", "genres": ["Fantasy", "Young Adult", "Fiction"], "avg_rating": 3.8, "num_reviews": 3130, "num_ratings": 16015, "about": "Colleen Oakes is the bestselling author of books for both teens and adults, including The Black Coats, Queen of Hearts Series, and The Wendy Darling Saga. She lives in North Denver with her husband and son. When not writing or plotting new books, Colleen can be found swimming, traveling or immersing herself in nerdy pop culture.She currently at work on her third YA fairytale series, a YA thriller and a fantasy collaboration. You can visit her webpage at: www.colleenoakes.org, find her on Facebook under Author Colleen Oakes or follow her on Twitter @ColleenOakes_."}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/57504.Harriet_Scott_Chessman", "name": "Harriet Scott Chessman", "genres": ["Fiction"], "influences": ["Virginia Woolf", "Edna O'Brien", "Alice McDermott", "Anton Chekhov"], "avg_rating": 3.72, "num_reviews": 300, "num_ratings": 2350, "about": "Harriet Scott Chessman is happy to announce the upcoming publication of her newest novel, The Lost Sketchbook of Edgar Degas (March 2017, Outpost 19), about Degas' five-month sojourn with his American cousins in New Orleans. Chessman's acclaimed novels include The Beauty of Ordinary Things, Lydia Cassatt Reading the Morning Paper, Someone Not Really Her Mother, and Ohio Angels. Her fiction has been translated into eight languages, and featured in The New York Times, The San Francisco Chronicle, NPR\u2019s All Things Considered, and Good Morning America. Chessman has taught English and American literature and creative writing at Yale University, Bread Loaf School of English, and Stanford University's Continuing Studies Program. She is working on Harriet Scott Chessman is happy to announce the upcoming publication of her newest novel, The Lost Sketchbook of Edgar Degas (March 2017, Outpost 19), about Degas' five-month sojourn with his American cousins in New Orleans. Chessman's acclaimed novels include The Beauty of Ordinary Things, Lydia Cassatt Reading the Morning Paper, Someone Not Really Her Mother, and Ohio Angels. Her fiction has been translated into eight languages, and featured in The New York Times, The San Francisco Chronicle, NPR\u2019s All Things Considered, and Good Morning America. Chessman has taught English and American literature and creative writing at Yale University, Bread Loaf School of English, and Stanford University's Continuing Studies Program. She is working on new short stories, to go into a story collection, to be titled \"Halliday's Treasures\" (the name of her story published in the Spring 2016 issue of Catamaran). She is also developing her libretto for MY LAI into a song / poem cycle. She lives now on the Shoreline of Connecticut, after twelve years in Palo Alto, California. ...more"}
{"url": "https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/7399837.Rob_Grimes", "name": "Rob Grimes", "genres": ["Fantasy", "Science Fiction", "Humor and Comedy"], "avg_rating": 4.8, "num_reviews": 5, "num_ratings": 20, "about": "So, who is Rob Grimes and why has he suddenly decided that he's an author?Good question... In fairness though, it's not that I've just decided, it's that I've only just realised. I mean, I've been writing for years; mostly factual stuff, technical manuals and instructions and things like that.Then I started to post sarcastic, wordy, and lengthy updates on Facebook that turned into The Chimping Dandy Blog, which in turn evolved into 'Mumblings of an Irate Pangolin' in the style of one of those hateful anthologies that newspaper columnists produce just before Christmas.Which itself spawned the first volume of the Windspider Chronicles 'Child of Air', which will be published towards the end of 2015 - But it' So, who is Rob Grimes and why has he suddenly decided that he's an author?Good question... In fairness though, it's not that I've just decided, it's that I've only just realised. I mean, I've been writing for years; mostly factual stuff, technical manuals and instructions and things like that.Then I started to post sarcastic, wordy, and lengthy updates on Facebook that turned into The Chimping Dandy Blog, which in turn evolved into 'Mumblings of an Irate Pangolin' in the style of one of those hateful anthologies that newspaper columnists produce just before Christmas.Which itself spawned the first volume of the Windspider Chronicles 'Child of Air', which will be published towards the end of 2015 - But it's great, there are airships and aliens and a villain that has a distinctly twirlable moustache (Although it features very little in the way of steampower and random cogs, because: done to death)I currently live in a nice-ish three storey house in Derby, UK; with my wife, two children and a dog called Mortimer, whose eyes point in wildly different directions.(Although if you offer me a decent publishing deal, maybe ten books? I'll move to LA at the drop of a hat.) ...more"}
